        <summary type="html"><![CDATA[The web doesnâ€™t stop at one server.]]></summary>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>The web doesnâ€™t stop at one server.<br>
<!-- -->So why should the decentralized web stop at one chain?</p>
<p>WTTP was designed for <strong>multi-network support</strong> from day one.</p>
<!-- -->
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-what-multi-network-means">ğŸŒ What Multi-Network Means<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/wttp-across-chains#-what-multi-network-means" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸŒ What Multi-Network Means" title="Direct link to ğŸŒ What Multi-Network Means">â€‹</a></h2>
<p>WTTP sites can be deployed on:</p>
<ul>
<li>Ethereum</li>
<li>Polygon</li>
<li>Base</li>
<li>Arbitrum</li>
<li>Fantom</li>
<li>Avalanche<br>
<!-- -->â€¦and more.</li>
</ul>
<p>Each network is just another home for your site.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-benefits">âš¡ Benefits<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/wttp-across-chains#-benefits" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to âš¡ Benefits" title="Direct link to âš¡ Benefits">â€‹</a></h2>
<ol>
<li>
<p><strong>Resilience</strong><br>
<!-- -->If one chain slows down, your site still lives elsewhere.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Choice</strong><br>
<!-- -->Developers can pick the network that best fits their needs (fees, speed, community).</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>Interoperability</strong><br>
<!-- -->A WTTP link doesnâ€™t care which chain itâ€™s onâ€”the protocol handles the rest.</p>
</li>
</ol>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-under-the-hood">ğŸ”§ Under the Hood<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/wttp-across-chains#-under-the-hood" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸ”§ Under the Hood" title="Direct link to ğŸ”§ Under the Hood">â€‹</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>The <strong>ProviderManager</strong> handles network switching.</li>
<li>The <strong>ContractManager</strong> keeps track of addresses across chains.</li>
<li>Your <code>wttp.config.json</code> file is the map that ties it all together.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<div class="alert alert--info" role="alert"><div><p>The web was always bigger than one machine.<br>
<!-- -->Now itâ€™s bigger than one blockchain.</p></div></div>]]></content>
