        <title type="html"><![CDATA[Royalties Built Into the Web]]></title>
        <id>https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web</id>
        <link href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web"/>
        <updated>2024-12-02T00:00:00.000Z</updated>
        <summary type="html"><![CDATA[For most of the webâ€™s history, creators got the short end of the stick.]]></summary>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>For most of the webâ€™s history, creators got the short end of the stick.<br>
<!-- -->Your content is copied, reshared, monetized â€” and you might never see a cent.</p>
<p>The <strong>Decentralized Internet Project (DIP)</strong> is changing that with WTTP.<br>
<!-- -->Hereâ€™s how <strong>royalties become part of the web itself</strong>.</p>
<!-- -->
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-the-problem-today">ğŸ¨ The Problem Today<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web#-the-problem-today" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸ¨ The Problem Today" title="Direct link to ğŸ¨ The Problem Today">â€‹</a></h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Artists</strong> upload to platforms that take most of the revenue.</li>
<li><strong>Developers</strong> share open-source code that powers million-dollar apps, without reward.</li>
<li><strong>Writers</strong> publish posts that others rehost, remix, or monetize.</li>
</ul>
<p>The common thread? Value flows <em>away</em> from the creator.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-wttps-solution">ğŸ’° WTTPâ€™s Solution<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web#-wttps-solution" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸ’° WTTPâ€™s Solution" title="Direct link to ğŸ’° WTTPâ€™s Solution">â€‹</a></h2>
<p>Every piece of content in WTTP is stored as a <strong>DataPoint</strong>.<br>
<!-- -->When someone reuses your DataPoint:</p>
<ol>
<li>They pay a small royalty.</li>
<li><strong>90%</strong> goes to you, the creator.</li>
<li><strong>10%</strong> supports the network.</li>
</ol>
<p>This happens <strong>automatically</strong>. No middlemen, no lawsuits, no ad networks.</p>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-why-this-works">ğŸ”‘ Why This Works<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web#-why-this-works" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸ”‘ Why This Works" title="Direct link to ğŸ”‘ Why This Works">â€‹</a></h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>Fairness baked in</strong>: the system itself enforces royalties.</li>
<li><strong>Global reach</strong>: your DataPoint works across all WTTP sites and networks.</li>
<li><strong>Incentives aligned</strong>: creators are rewarded for making things worth reusing.</li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-a-simple-example">ğŸ§© A Simple Example<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web#-a-simple-example" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸ§© A Simple Example" title="Direct link to ğŸ§© A Simple Example">â€‹</a></h2>
<p>Letâ€™s say you upload an image to WTTP.</p>
<ul>
<li>A blogger uses it in their article.</li>
<li>A developer reuses it in an app.</li>
<li>A designer builds on it in their portfolio.</li>
</ul>
<p>Each reuse triggers a royalty payment back to you. The more your work travels, the more you earn.</p>
<hr>
<div class="alert alert--info" role="alert"><div><p>Think of it as <strong>Web3â€™s answer to Creative Commons</strong>: you decide what to share, and if itâ€™s reused, the network pays you fairly.</p></div></div>
<hr>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="-why-it-matters">ğŸš€ Why It Matters<a href="https://docs.thedip.net/blog/royalties-on-the-web#-why-it-matters" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to ğŸš€ Why It Matters" title="Direct link to ğŸš€ Why It Matters">â€‹</a></h2>
<p>Royalties change the economics of the web.<br>
<!-- -->Instead of â€œwinner-takes-allâ€ platforms, we get a <strong>commons where creators are valued</strong>.</p>
<p>Thatâ€™s what DIP is about.<br>
<!-- -->Thatâ€™s why WTTP matters.</p>]]></content>
